title: ‘Air raid sirens blaring’: Latest on major Russian attack on Kyiv
description: Former chair of Monash University Ukrainian Foundation Michael Lawriwsky discusses the latest updates of a major Russian attack on Kyiv.  Kyiv has had air raid sirens "blaring” until the early morning, Mr Lawriwsky told Sky News Australia.  “They want to overrun them with all these drones and missiles together.”

title: Zelensky to have ‘tough meeting’ with President Trump in Florida
description: Former chair of Monash University Ukrainian Foundation Michael Lawriwsky expects President Zelensky to have a “tough meeting” with President Donald Trump in Florida.  “The twenty points that Zelensky is bringing to Trump, they’re not going to be acceptable to the Russians,” Mr Lawriwsky told Sky News Australia.  “Trump will probably try to threaten or cause Zelensky to give in on certain items.”

title: Labor government introduces life saving funding
description: $5 million will be spent on improving water safety education for people from diverse backgrounds.  Funding will help surf lifeguards keep swimmers safe during the peak summer season.  $100,000 will also be used to restock first-aid supplies at the North Bondi and Bondi surf lifesaving clubs.

title: ‘Eighty per cent’ agree: Qld MP renews calls for death penalty for terrorists
description: The Courier Mail Columnist Des Houghton discusses Queensland MP Christian Rowan renewing calls for the death penalty to be introduced for terrorists.  “This is a conversation we should have, especially involving terrorist acts where there are mass casualties,” Mr Houghton told Sky News Australia.  “On our online poll, in the paper today … eighty per cent of people agree with him.”

title: Trump calls the Epstein Files a hoax
description: US President Donald Trump is blaming the Democrats for the latest Epstein files release and is accusing them of pushing a hoax.  "Now one million more pages on Epstein are found. DOJ is being forced to spend all of its time on this Democrat inspired Hoax,” Mr Trump said.  According to the US government, the rest of the Epstein files will be released in the new year.

title: International Space Station turns 25
description: For the past 25 years, astronauts have lived and worked on the International Space Station to conduct research on the human body in microgravity.  Hopes are set on returning people to the moon, but scientists say there are still big gaps in the understanding of survival beyond the Earth's atmosphere.    Within the next few weeks, astronauts will launch on a mission around the moon for the first time in 53 years.

title: Emergency warning for New York snow storm
description: New York’s Governor has declared a state of emergency as residents prepare for extreme weather conditions.  Between twelve and thirty centimeters of snow is expected to fall in some areas.  Forecasters predict New York City will see its highest snowfall total since 2022.

title: Russia will ‘use any excuse’ to continue war in Ukraine
description: Former chair of Monash University Ukrainian Foundation Michael Lawriwsky claims Russia will “use any excuse” to continue the war amid an attack on Kyiv.  “Trump can secure a ceasefire or at least a stop to the war is to give Ukraine overwhelming military force," Mr Lawriwsky told Sky News Australia.  "Also backed up by very, very good sanctions.  “Putin will fight to the bitter end, to the last Russian soldier that there is to try to achieve his goal.”

title: Sussan Ley ‘shows leadership’ in calling for Parliament to reconvene
description: Former Liberal MP Keith Wolahan says that Sussan Ley “is right” in calling for Parliament to reconvene immediately to pass laws to combat antisemitism.  “She’s showing the leadership that we desperately want the Prime Minister to show,” Mr Wolahan told Sky News Australia.  “There’s a sense of sadness that this event is being put in a box and is going to stay in 2025.”

title: State royal commission ‘not good enough’ to combat antisemitism and terrorism
description: Former Liberal MP Keith Wolahan claims that a NSW state royal commission is “not good enough” to combat antisemitism and terrorism.  “The scourge of antisemitism and terrorism is a national issue,” Mr Wolahan told Sky News Australia.  “We sadly have recent experience of state royal commissions not being good enough.  “We need a federal royal commission.”

title: ‘Missing in action’: Anthony Albanese blasted for lack of leadership
description: Former Liberal MP Keith Wolahan claims Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has been “missing in action” in his leadership.  “At a more immediate level, we need to see more leadership from the Prime Minister,” Mr Wolahan told Sky News Australia.  “He’s the one who holds that title and is in the office, and again he’s been missing in action.”

title: 'Finding the line': Crackdown on civil liberties should ‘tread carefully’
description: Former Liberal MP Keith Wolahan says a crackdown on civil liberties should “tread carefully” on finding out where the line is.  Mr Wolahan told Sky News Australia, “if only that was the answer” to combating antisemitism and extremism.  “We should always tread carefully when we’re restricting freedom of speech, freedom of movement.”

title: Sydney NYE to pause for victims of Bondi attack
description: Sydney will pause on New Year's Eve to remember the victims of the Bondi attack.  The Harbor Bridge will shine white with the image of a dove, before a minute’s silence.  Security will be boosted at the event, including additional CCTV.

title: Hundreds brave traditional icy winter swim in Prague
description: Hundreds of people have braved icy waters in a traditional mid-winter swim in Prague.  Three hundred and thirty swimmers plunged into the water, with temperatures just above freezing.  The tradition of winter swimming in the Czech capital dates back over a hundred years.

title: Thousands of households left without power after major Russian attack on Kyiv
description: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky says Kyiv is still under attack from Russian drones after heavy strikes.  With temperatures just above freezing, over 320,000 households in Kyiv have been left without power or heating.  President Zelensky says almost 500 drones were launched overnight.
